SECTION 4. Section 22-29-9 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1986,
24
Chapter 94, Section 9, as amended) is amended to read:
25 HAFC/HB 47
Page 8

1 "22-29-9. PARTICIPATION--WAIVERS.--
2 A. School districts and charter schools shall
3 participate in the authority, unless the school district or
4 charter school is granted a waiver by the board; provided
5 that beginning July 1, 2027, the board shall not grant a
6 waiver for health, disability income or term life insurance.
7 B. In determining whether a waiver should be
8 granted, the board shall establish minimum benefit and
9 financial standards for the desired line of coverage. These
10 minimum benefit and financial standards and the proposed time
11 schedule for responsive offers shall be sent to all school
12 districts and charter schools at the time the request for
13 proposals for the desired line of coverage is issued. Any
14 school district or charter school seeking a waiver of
15 coverage shall match the minimum benefit and financial
16 standards set forth in the request for proposals for the
desired line of coverage. School districts and charter
17
schools shall submit documentation of their proposals
18
matching the board's minimum benefit and financial
19
requirements prior to the deadline established by the board.
20
The authority has the power to approve or disapprove a waiver
21
of participation based on the documentation submitted by the
22
school district or charter school regarding the benefit and
23
financial standards established by the board. The board
24
shall grant a waiver to a school district or charter school
25 HAFC/HB 47
Page 9

1 that requests a waiver and that has met the minimum benefit
2 and financial standards within the time schedule established
3 by the board. Once the board awards the insurance contract,
4 no school district or charter school shall be granted a
5 waiver for the entire term of the contract.
6 C. Prior to July 1, 2027, a school district or
7 charter school granted a waiver of participation for health
8 insurance shall be required to petition for participation in
9 other kinds of group insurance coverage and shall be required
10 to meet the requirements established by the authority prior
11 to participation in other kinds of group insurance coverage.
12 A school district or charter school that has been granted a
13 waiver shall be prohibited from participating in the coverage
14 for which a waiver was granted for the entire term of the
15 authority's insurance contract. Provided, however, that if
16 the authority contracts for a line or lines of coverage for a
period of eight years, the board may establish procedures and
17
preconditions for authorizing a school district or charter
18
school that has been granted a waiver to again participate in
19
the coverage after the expiration of the first four years of
20
coverage. A waiver of health, disability income or term life
21
insurance shall not be effective after June 30, 2027.
22
D. Any school district or charter school granted a
23
waiver of participation for workers' compensation shall be
24
required to petition for participation in other risk-related
25 HAFC/HB 47
Page 10

1 coverages and shall be required to meet the requirements
2 established by the authority prior to participation in other
3 kinds of risk-related coverages. A school district or
4 charter school that has been granted a waiver shall be
5 prohibited from participating in the coverage for which a
6 waiver was granted for the entire term of the authority's
7 insurance contract.
8 E. Educational entities may petition the authority
9 for permission to participate in the insurance coverage
10 provided by the authority. To protect the stability of the
11 fund, the authority shall establish reasonable terms and
12 conditions for participation by educational entities.
13 F. A participating school district or charter
14 school may separately provide for coverage additional to that
15 offered by the authority.
16 G. School districts, charter schools or the
authority, as appropriate, may provide for marketing and
17
servicing to be done by licensed insurance agents or brokers
18
who should receive reasonable compensation for their
19
services."
